{"id":"2207.10620","submitter":"Lukas Liehr","authors":"Philipp Grohs, Lukas Liehr, Martin Rathmair","title":"Multi-window STFT phase retrieval: lattice uniqueness","comments":"18 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.FA math.CV","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Short-time Fourier transform (STFT) phase retrieval refers to the\nreconstruction of a signal $f$ from its spectrogram, i.e., the magnitudes of\nits STFT $$V_gf(x,\\omega):=\\int_{\\mathbb{R}}f(t)\\overline{g(t-x)}e^{-2\\pi\nit\\omega}dt,$$ and appears as a central problem in several applications,\nincluding coherent diffraction imaging and audio processing. It is known that\nfor several window functions $g$, any function $f\\in L^2(\\mathbb{R})$ can be\nreconstructed from the full spectrogram $|V_g f(\\mathbb{R}^2)|$ but in practice\nthe reconstruction needs to be achieved only from discrete samples of\n$|V_gf(\\Lambda)|$, typically from a lattice $\\Lambda=A\\mathbb{Z}^2$. It turns\nout that the sampled problem becomes much more subtle: recently established\ndiscretization barriers state that uniqueness via lattice sampling is never\nachievable in $L^2(\\mathbb{R})$, irrespective of the window function $g$ and\nthe density of the lattice. In the present paper we therefore initiate the\nstudy of multi-window STFT phase retrieval. We discover a novel connection\nbetween multi-window STFT phase retrieval and sampling in Fock space, allowing\nus to establish uniqueness results on the recoverability of square-integrable\nfunctions from spectrogram samples located on lattices. Precisely, we specify\nconditions on window functions $g_1,\\dots,g_4\\in L^2(\\mathbb{R})$ such that\nevery $f\\in L^2(\\mathbb{R})$ is determined up to a global phase by\n$$\\left(|V_{g_1}f(A\\mathbb{Z}^2)|,\\ldots,|V_{g_4}f(A\\mathbb{Z}^2)|\\right)$$\nwhenever $A\\in\\mathrm{GL}_2(\\mathbb{R})$ satisfies the density condition $|\\det\nA|^{-1}\\geq4$. For real-valued signals $f\\in L^2(\\mathbb{R},\\mathbb{R})$ it\nsuffices that $|\\det A|^{-1}\\geq2$. Corresponding results for irregular\nsampling are also shown. Our results thereby overcome the aforementioned\ndiscretization barriers and constitute the first ever general uniqueness result\nfor sampled STFT phase retrieval.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 21 Jul 2022 17:28:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 22 Jul 2022 15:04:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-26"}
{"id":"2207.10621","submitter":"Evgenii A. Kuznetsov","authors":"E.A. Kuznetsov and E.A. Mikhailov","title":"Slipping flows and their breaking","comments":"20 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.aop.2022.169088","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn astro-ph.SR nlin.PS","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The process of breaking of inviscid incompressible flows along a rigid body\nwith slipping boundary conditions is studied. Such slipping flows are\ncompressible, which is the main reason for the formation of a singularity for\nthe gradient of the velocity component parallel to rigid border. Slipping flows\nare studied analytically in the framework of two- and three-dimensional\ninviscid Prandtl equations. Criteria for a gradient catastrophe are found in\nboth cases. For 2D Prandtl equations breaking takes place both for the parallel\nvelocity along the boundary and for the vorticity gradient. For\nthree-dimensional Prandtl flows, breaking, i.e. the formation of a fold in a\nfinite time, occurs for the symmetric part of the velocity gradient tensor, as\nwell as for the antisymmetric part - vorticity. The problem of the formation of\nvelocity gradients for flows between two parallel plates is studied numerically\nin the framework of two-dimensional Euler equations. It is shown that the\nmaximum velocity gradient grows exponentially with time on a rigid boundary\nwith a simultaneous increase in the vorticity gradient according to a double\nexponential law. Careful analysis shows that this process is nothing more than\nthe folding, with a power-law relationship between the maximum velocity\ngradient and its width: $% \\max|u_x|\\propto \\ell^{-2/3}$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 21 Jul 2022 17:28:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-28"}
